'''Kosodate Jizō''' (子育地蔵) is a [[:en:Jizō Bosatsu|Jizō statue]] (地蔵尊), a form of [[Stone Buddha|Stone Buddha statue]] (石仏), enshrined in a [[Jizō Hall]] (地蔵堂) located in {{ill|Iwamurada, Saku, Nagano|ja|岩村田|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Iwamurada, Saku, Nagano|1=Iwamurada|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q22127357}}, {{ill|Saku, Nagano|en|Saku, Nagano|qid=Q495821|lt=Saku, Nagano|1=Saku, Nagano}}, {{ill|Nagano Prefecture|en|Nagano Prefecture|qid=Q127877|lt=Nagano Prefecture|1=Nagano Prefecture}}.

== Overview ==

Kosodate Jizō (子育地蔵) is enshrined in the Jizō Hall in the Yanagidō area of {{ill|Iwamurada, Saku, Nagano|ja|岩村田|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Iwamurada, Saku, Nagano|1=Iwamurada|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q22127357}}, {{ill|Saku, Nagano|en|Saku, Nagano|qid=Q495821|lt=Saku, Nagano|1=Saku, Nagano}}, {{ill|Nagano Prefecture|en|Nagano Prefecture|qid=Q127877|lt=Nagano Prefecture|1=Nagano Prefecture}}. It is still worshiped today, with beliefs that praying to it will cure children of ailments such as [[:en:Blisters|blisters]] (水疱), [[:en:colds|colds]] (風邪), {{ill|measles|en|measles|qid=Q79793|lt=measles|1=Measles}} (麻疹), and {{ill|mumps|en|mumps|qid=Q176741|lt=mumps|1=Mumps}} (おたふく風邪), or ensure that they grow up strong and healthy. 

In {{ill|1932|en|1932|qid=Q18743|lt=Showa 7|1=1932}} ({{ill|1932|en|1932|qid=Q18743|lt=1932 AD|1=1932}}), the statue was relocated from the Tsuishi area of Iwamurada to the Yanagidō area. Each autumn, a {{ill|Ennichi|en|Ennichi|qid=Q985655|lt=Ennichi|1=Ennichi}} (festival day) is held, during which the head priest of the nearby {{ill|Sainen-ji (Saku)|ja|西念寺|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sainen-ji (Saku)|1=Sainenji|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11628254}} chants sutras, and many children and devotees come to pay their respects. A sorrowful poem associated with the statue reads:

*"Sararawareshi / so ga osanago yo / Jizō-son / hateshinaku ou / Tsuishi no mori"*

(*"Carried away / my ancestor's young child / Jizō-son / endlessly pursued / in Tsuishi's forest."*)

The pedestal stone of the Jizō statue is made from one of the "Seven Stones of Iwamurada" (岩村田七石)—specifically, a part of the "Myōto Ishi" (夫婦石, "Husband-and-Wife Stone"). The seven stones include {{ill|Tsuishi|ja|蔦石|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsuishi|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, {{ill|Tsubure Ishi|ja|潰石|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsubure Ishi|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, {{ill|Aka Ishi|ja|赤石|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Aka Ishi|1=Akaishi, Tahara|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q28057245}}, {{ill|Myōto Ishi|ja|夫婦石|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Myōto Ishi|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 夫婦岩|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 夫婦岩|1=Meoto Iwa|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q333875}}, {{ill|Shinano Ishi|ja|信濃石|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinano Ishi|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, {{ill|Kurakake Ishi|ja|鞍掛石|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kurakake Ishi|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, and {{ill|Katsuta Ishi|ja|勝田石|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Katsuta Ishi|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}.

It is said that before the relocation, there was already another Kosodate Jizō in Tsuishi. During the {{ill|Tenshō era|ja|天正年間|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenshō era|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 天正|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 天正|1=Tenshō (Momoyama period)|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q1145058}} of the {{ill|Azuchi–Momoyama period|en|Azuchi–Momoyama period|qid=Q319531|lt=Azuchi-Momoyama period|1=Azuchi–Momoyama period}}, many residents of Iwamurada migrated to {{ill|Fujioka, Gunma|en|Fujioka, Gunma|qid=Q596486|lt=Fujioka, Gunma|1=Fujioka, Gunma}} in {{ill|Kōzuke Province|en|Kōzuke Province|qid=Q1054838|lt=Kōzuke Province|1=Kōzuke Province}}. They carried this earlier Jizō statue on their backs and enshrined it in Miyamoto-chō (宮本町) in Fujioka.

